Linley,<br><br>
If I may, I would like to make a suggestion to you that I made to another participant in our &quot;Focus&quot; group.  She too had a father who would not talk about the war.  My suggestion:  buy him a small tape recorder for dictating, and a number of tapes.  Also buy a safety deposite box, and give him the only key.  Then ask him to take same time and put his thoughts, experiences, and hopes and dreams onto tape, and lock them away.  The box would only be opened at his wish, or after his death.  This way, maybe you could show how important this aspect of your family history is to you, and begin a dialog.  If he elects to tape but doesn't wish people to hear it until after his death, honor his wish.  There are some things about this war which no one probably wants to have generally known, and there are some things which are secret still.  This is one way that you may be able to gain that history which so far has not been open to you.  Best wishes, and enjoy!
